So what this means is whenever you're doing votes with the look looks like with the specifically with the cli, it'll simulate and use the compute unit limitation that was returned by the simulated transaction to make sure that your transaction uses less compute overall. So why is this important and why should you do this with your normal transactions is overall there is a compute limit cap on transactions per block. I think it's 48 million and if you request compute units, those requested ones and you don't use them, those will make your users. They'll make the transaction costs more for the priority fees for your users. So you want to lower them as much as possible so the users pay less as well as because you're requesting more, you might get packed into the block later or not get or not get packed into the block at all.
